      "t` is not to be confused with `t` in `X_t`. \n\n   Actually, perhaps we can map `t` to `τ(ω) = t`, which is a stopping time if `t` is fixed, and then `{X_t}` is a subset of `{X_τ}`. \n\n   If `{X_τ}` is uniformly integrable, then `{X_t}` is also uniformly integrable, hence `UniformIntegrable X 1 P`.\n\n   For the converse, perhaps if `X_t` is uniformly integrable, then for any bounded stopping time `τ`, `X_τ` is bounded by some `X_t`.\n\nBut perhaps in the case of `X` a `Martingale`, we can say that for any `t`, `X_t` is uniformly integrable, but for `τ ≤ t`, `X_τ` is a projection of `X_t`, hence is also uniformly integrable. \n\nBut perhaps not directly. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use that `X_t` is uniformly integrable implies that `X_τ` is uniformly integrable, because we can write `X_τ` as a conditional expectation of `X_t`, but we would need that `t` is greater than all `τ`, which is not always the case. \n\nBut perhaps we can use a different approach: because `X_t` is uniformly integrable, and in particular integrable, then for any finite stopping time `τ`, `X_τ` is `L¹`, but we would need to prove that the set `{X_τ}` is uniformly integrable. \n\nBut perhaps there is no general relation between these two notions. \n\nBut perhaps in fact, these two notions are equivalent in general, even without assuming that `X` is a `Martingale`: \n\n`ClassD X 𝓕 P` iff `UniformIntegrable X 1 P`. \n\nBut it is not. \n\nConsider `X_t(ω) = t`, and `P` the uniform measure on `[0,1]`, then `X_t` is not uniformly integrable in `t`, but `{X_τ}` is not uniformly integrable if we consider `τ(ω) = 1/ω` if `ω ≠ 0`, but perhaps not bounded. \n\nAlternatively, take `X_t = t`, then `UniformIntegrable X 1 P` is false, because for large `t`, `X_t` is not in `L¹`, but if we take `ι = [0,1]`, then `X_t ∈ L¹`, and `ClassD X 𝓕 P` would require that `{X_τ, τ bounded}` is uniformly integrable, which it is not (take `τ_n = 1 - 1/n`, then `X_{τ_n} = 1 - 1/n`, not uniformly integrable).