### ```lean
closed under finite intersections.

We will use the fact that for a measurable function f and a measure μ,
if the set of points where f(x) ≠ c is measurable, then the set {x | f(x) < c}
is measurable. This is because {x | f(x) < c} = E \ {x | f(x) ≠ c}, and the complement of a measurable set is measurable.

However, in our case, f(x) = x + sin(x) is continuous and thus measurable, and {x | x + sin(x) ≠ c} is the complement of a closed set (since x + sin(x) is continuous), hence measurable. Therefore, {x | x + sin(x) < c} is measurable as the complement of a measurable set.

Alternatively, since x + sin(x) is continuous, the set {x | x + sin(x) < c} is open, hence measurable.

But to formalize this, we need to show that {x | x + sin(x) < c} is an open set. Since x ↦ x + sin(x) is continuous, the preimage of the open interval (-∞, c) is open. Hence, the set {x | x + sin(x) < c} is open, and therefore measurable.

### Formal Proof Sketch:
1. Define f(x) = x + sin(x).
2. Show that f is continuous.
3. The set {x | f(x) < c} is the preimage of (-∞, c) under f, hence it is open.
4. An open set is measurable, so {x | f(x) < c} is measurable.

